Linear Models with Heights

We will be looking at height and weight data for 12 year old kids on a factorial diet of high or low protein and high or low carbs (height_weight.csv). The average number of hours of TV each week for each child was also tracked. We will be exploring how these factors (diet and TV time) affect childrens growth.

Q3 Another way to summarize data from statistical models is to use Anova() from the car library, instead of summary(). This method is great because you can designate which test statistic you will use, and which type of sums of squares you will use. You can read the specifications here. Install the car library and summarize your model for Q2 using an F statistic with type III sums of squares. What are the differences between this and the model above?

library(car)

Anova(test_2, test.statistic = "F", type = "III")

Q9 Write a paragraph for both the statistical methods and results for questions 7 and 8 as if you were writing these for a publication. This will be practice for your final module project with your own data. Remember to just stick to the model interpretations for the results section.

Statistical Methods: To determine if a childs weight is influenced by the number of hours of TV watched and their diet, we used a linear model with weight as the dependent variable, and the interaction of hours of tv watched, diet carbohydrates and diet protein as the independent variables. We used a backward statistical design, where we started with the full interactive model, and if interactions were not significant, we dropped them until we either found significant terms, or reached a fully additive model.

Statistical Results: We did not find a significant effect of carbohydrates consumed on a childs weight, but we found that weight was significantly influenced by the interaction of the number of hours of TV watched and the protein in a childs diet. When a child has a higher protein diet, they increase weight faster as they watch more hours of TV than when they have a lower protein diet.
